          "exp": "Correct Answer: D\nRationale: The convention being tested is punctuation use between two main clauses. In this choice, a colon is correctly used to mark the boundary between one main clause (\"goats are notoriously indiscriminate\") and another main clause (\"they will devour all kinds of shrubs and weeds\") and to introduce the following explanation of goats’ nondiscriminatory behavior when it comes to what they eat.\nWhat's Being Tested: The first clause makes a complete claim ('goats are notoriously indiscriminate') and the second\nclause explains exactly what that means. A colon is the perfect tool here: it signals that what follows\ndirectly illustrates or elaborates on what came before.\nRule / Formula: [Complete clause]: [explanation or elaboration]\nA colon must be preceded by a grammatically complete independent clause. The information after the colon\nexpands on, defines, or exemplifies the first clause. Never use a colon after an incomplete phrase like 'such as'\nor in the middle of a verb phrase.\nWhy the Other Choices Are Wrong:\nA: when coordinating two longer main clauses such as these, it’s conventional to use a comma before the coordinating conjunction. Furthermore, the conjunction \"and\" fails to indicate that what follows is an explanation of goats’ nondiscriminatory behavior when it comes to their diets.\nB: it results in a comma splice. A comma can’t be used in this way to join two main clauses (\"goats…indiscriminate\" and \"they…weeds\").\nC: it results in a run-on sentence. The two main clauses (\"goats…indiscriminate\" and \"they…weeds\") are fused without punctuation and/or a conjunction.",
