          "exp": "Correct Answer: C\nRationale: The convention being tested is the use of verbs to express tense. In this choice, the present tense verb “experiences” is consistent with the other present tense verbs (e.g., “connects” and “prepares”) used to describe the events in Truong’s novels. Furthermore, it’s conventional to use the present tense when discussing a literary work.\nWhat's Being Tested: When discussing events in a work of literature, English uses the literary present tense. The\nsurrounding verbs 'connects' and 'prepares' are both present tense, so the missing verb must also be\npresent tense to stay consistent.\nRule / Formula: Literary present: use present tense (connects, experiences, says) when discussing fictional\nevents\nThe literary present tense applies whenever you are summarizing or analyzing what happens in a novel, poem,\nplay, or film. It treats the events as eternally occurring on the page. Switching to past tense in the middle of a\nliterary summary is an error unless there's a specific reason to mark something as earlier.\nWhy the Other Choices Are Wrong:\nA: the past tense verb “experienced” isn’t consistent with the other present tense verbs used to describe the events in Truong’s novels.\nB: the past perfect tense verb “had experienced” isn’t consistent with the other present tense verbs used to describe the events in Truong’s novels.\nD: the future progressive tense verb “will be experiencing” isn’t consistent with the other present tense verbs used to describe the events in Truong’s novels.",
