          "exp": "Correct Answer: B\nRationale: The convention being tested is punctuation between a supplementary element and a main clause. This choice correctly uses a comma to mark the boundary between the supplementary phrase (“While...1947”), which indicates when the action occurred, and the main clause (“Howe had a handheld camera operator wear roller skates”).\nWhat's Being Tested: The phrase 'While filming a boxing match for the movie Body and Soul (1947)' is an introductory\nsupplementary element that sets the scene. A comma after it marks the boundary between this\nphrase and the main clause that follows.\nRule / Formula: [Introductory supplementary phrase], [Main clause] — comma separates the phrase from the\nclause\nIntroductory elements (phrases that set time, place, or context before the main clause) are always followed by a\ncomma. The parenthetical '(1947)' is part of the introductory phrase; the comma belongs after the closing\nparenthesis. A conjunction like 'and' is not needed and would be incorrect here.\nWhy the Other Choices Are Wrong:\nA: a comma paired with the conjunction “and” can’t be used in this way to mark the boundary between the supplementary element (“While…1947”) and the main clause (“Howe…skates”).\nC: the conjunction “and” can’t be used in this way to join the supplementary element (“While…1947”) and the main clause (“Howe…skates”).\nD: it fails to mark the boundary between the supplementary element and the main clause with appropriate punctuation.",
