          "exp": "Correct Answer: B\nRationale: The convention being tested is subject-verb agreement. The singular verb \"is\" agrees in number with the singular subject \"the shape.\"\nWhat's Being Tested: The subject is 'the shape' (singular), not 'ears.' The phrase 'of each statue's ears' is a prepositional modifier —\nignore it when identifying the subject. 'Like the shape of each person's ears' is a parenthetical comparison,\nalso not the subject.\nRule / Formula: [The shape] of [plural modifier], like [comparison], [singular verb]\nA classic subject–verb agreement trap: plural nouns appear between the real subject and the verb. Cross out\n'of each statue's ears' and 'like the shape of each person's ears' — you're left with 'the shape ___ unique,' which\nclearly needs 'is.'\nWhy the Other Choices Are Wrong:\nA: the plural verb \"are\" doesn’t agree in number with the singular subject \"the shape.\"\nC: the plural verb \"were\" doesn’t agree in number with the singular subject \"the shape.\"\nD: the plural verb \"have been\" doesn’t agree in number with the singular subject \"the shape.\"",
