          "exp": "Correct Answer: D\nRationale: The convention being tested is the use of punctuation between titles and proper nouns. No punctuation is needed to set off the coordinated noun phrase \"Chile and Luxembourg\" from the title that describes the two countries, \"fellow OECD nations.\" Because the proper nouns \"Chile and Luxembourg\" are essential information identifying the \"fellow OECD nations,\" no punctuation is necessary.\nWhat's Being Tested: 'Chile and Luxembourg' are the essential identifiers of which OECD nations are being discussed. Because\nthey're restrictive (you can't remove them without making the sentence vague), no punctuation separates them\nfrom 'fellow OECD nations.'\nRule / Formula: [Title/category] [Essential names] — no punctuation when names are the identity of the category\nIf you could answer the question 'Which OECD nations?' by removing the names and still make sense, commas\nmight be fine. But here, without 'Chile and Luxembourg,' the reader doesn't know which nations are meant. That\nmakes them restrictive — no commas.\nWhy the Other Choices Are Wrong:\nA: no punctuation is needed between the country names (\"Chile and Luxembourg\") and the title (\"fellow OECD nations\") describing them. Further, setting the countries’ names off with commas suggests that they could be removed without affecting the coherence of the sentence, which isn’t the case.\nB: no punctuation is needed between the country names (\"Chile and Luxembourg\") and the title (\"fellow OECD nations\") describing them.\nC: no punctuation is needed between the country names (\"Chile and Luxembourg\") and the title (\"fellow OECD nations\") describing them. Placing a colon after \"nations\" would confusingly suggest that these were the costs of the basket of goods for \"fellow OECD nations\" in general, not for Chile and Luxembourg specifically.",
