          "exp": "Correct Answer: D\nRationale: The convention being tested is the use of a colon within a sentence. In this choice, the colon correctly introduces the following explanation of the different functions of genomes and epigenomes.\nWhat's Being Tested: The first clause makes a claim (cells develop different functions). What follows explains exactly what those\ndifferent functions are. A colon is used after a complete clause to introduce an elaborating explanation.\nRule / Formula: [Complete clause]: [explanation of what was just stated]\nRemember: the colon means 'here is what I mean' or 'specifically.' The material before the colon must be a\ncomplete independent clause. A comma alone would create a comma splice. 'And,' is awkward and fails to\nsignal explanation.\nWhy the Other Choices Are Wrong:\nA: it results in a run-on sentence. The two main clauses (\"The relationship…functions\" and \"whereas… expressed\") are fused without punctuation and/or a conjunction.\nB: it results in a comma splice. A comma can’t be used in this way to join two main clauses (\"The relationship…functions\" and \"whereas…expressed\").\nC: Without a comma preceding it, the conjunction \"and\" can’t be used in this way to join two main clauses. Furthermore, \"and\" fails to indicate that what follows is an explanation of how cells with identical DNA develop different functions.",
